ONEWATER MARINE INC. (NASDAQ: ONEW)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended December 31, 2025
(Form 10-Q, reported January 29, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: The Company's revenue grew to $380.6m in Q1 FY26 from $375.8m in Q1 FY25, representing a 1.3% YoY increase; same-store sales were flat versus the prior-year period, with growth driven by mix shift rather than unit demand. Beneath the headline, new-boat sales declined 6% while pre-owned sales surged 24%, signalling that consumer demand has rotated to lower-ticket, value-oriented purchases — consistent with continued post-COVID normalisation and elevated consumer financing rates. Revenue narrowly beat the Zacks consensus of $380.3m and management reiterated FY26 guidance of $1.83bn–$1.93bn in revenue, Adjusted EBITDA of $65m–$85m, and adjusted diluted EPS of $0.25–$0.75, with the outlook predicated on an industry assumed to be flat to down low single digits.

> Profitability: The Company's profitability improved on the bottom line despite continued operating-level pressure. Gross margin expanded 110 bps YoY to 23.5% in Q1 FY26 from 22.4% in Q1 FY25, the first quarterly margin expansion in two years, driven by favourable model mix and benefits from completed brand-exit and portfolio-optimisation efforts. Operating margin contracted to (1.4%) in Q1 FY26 from (0.5%) in Q1 FY25, with operating loss widening to ($5.2m) from ($2.0m), as the $7.1m non-cash impairment charge related to the adjustment of the carrying value of assets held for sale (Distribution segment) more than offset the underlying gross margin expansion; SG&A was $81.4m in Q1 FY26 (21.4% of revenue) versus $79.1m (21.0%) in Q1 FY25, with the percentage increase driven by higher variable personnel costs including sales commissions. Net loss narrowed materially to ($7.7m) in Q1 FY26 from ($13.6m) in Q1 FY25, despite the wider operating loss, with the improvement driven by lower interest expense following the term-loan paydown and lower one-time charges flowing through other expense; Adjusted EBITDA increased 88.9% to $3.6m from $1.9m in the prior-year quarter.

> Cash Flows: Q1 FY26 cash from operating activities is not separately disclosed in the earnings release, but the cash position deteriorated by $20.0m sequentially (from $52.2m at September 30, 2025 to $32.2m at December 31, 2025), implying continued cash absorption from seasonal inventory build, working-capital pressure, and interest service. The Company's seasonal Q1 working-capital pattern (boat show stocking, pre-spring inventory positioning) typically consumes cash, with the H2 selling season expected to reverse this; with long-term debt simultaneously reduced by $12.7m in the quarter (from $412.1m to $399.4m), the cash decline reflects both operating absorption and active deleveraging via debt paydown.

> Liquidity and debt position: As of December 31, 2025, total liquidity was approximately $46m, including $32m of cash and cash equivalents plus availability on credit facilities — a meaningful sequential erosion from ~$67m at September 30, 2025 and structurally thin for a business of this scale. Total inventory decreased to $602m at December 31, 2025 from $637m at December 31, 2024, reflecting inventory reclassified as held for sale and disciplined inventory optimisation. Total debt comprises $399.4m of long-term debt with adjusted long-term net debt (net of $32.2m cash) at 5.1 times trailing twelve-month Adjusted EBITDA, flat sequentially despite the absolute debt reduction — confirming EBITDA-denominator pressure persists; management indicated proceeds from the held-for-sale Distribution divestiture would be used to cut borrowings, with net leverage potentially declining to approximately 4.0x post-transaction. The senior secured term loan matures July 31, 2027 and the floor-plan credit facility matures March 1, 2027 (capacity up to $497m plus $38m overtrade).

> Working Capital: Working capital position remained constrained — total inventory of $602m at Q1 FY26 vs $637m at Q1 FY25 represents a (5.5%) YoY decline, partly mechanical (held-for-sale reclassification) and partly active inventory discipline. Pre-owned mix lift (+24% YoY) is improving inventory turns, while the new-boat softness ((6%) YoY) underscores why floor-plan utilisation remains the dominant working-capital lever. Days inventory outstanding remained elevated against the seasonal Q1 stocking cycle, and the Company continues to fund a large portion of inventory through floor-plan financing rather than through working-capital cash generation.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: $52.8m of Distribution segment assets remain classified as held for sale at December 31, 2025; no definitive agreement has been entered into and management cannot provide additional comments regarding the potential for completing a transaction. The $7.1m Q1 FY26 impairment is a direct mark-to-market of these held-for-sale assets to expected fair value, net of costs to sell, with the targeted closing window aligning with the FY25 10-K disclosure on exploring alternative sources of cash to meet debt obligations by March 31, 2026. Strategic brand exits announced in FY25 are now substantially complete and beginning to flow through as margin expansion, supporting management's "margin expansion in FY26" thesis.

> Going Concern: The FY25 Form 10-K (filed December 15, 2025) does not include an explicit "substantial doubt" statement; however, it flagged the need to explore alternative sources of cash proceeds to meet debt obligations by March 31, 2026, and the Q1 FY26 disclosure confirms negotiations on the Distribution divestiture remain ongoing without a definitive agreement. Combined with sequential liquidity erosion of $21m (from $67m to $46m), 5.1x net leverage, and an unsigned divestiture as the primary deleveraging mechanism, the next 60–90 days (through end-March 2026) represent the binding execution window for management's deleveraging plan.

> Management Change: Effective August 19, 2025, the Company formalised a top-of-house leadership change: Austin Singleton was appointed Executive Chairman of the Board (from Chief Executive Officer), Anthony Aisquith was named Chief Executive Officer (from President and COO), Jack Ezzell was appointed Chief Operating Officer in addition to his existing Chief Financial Officer role, and John F. Schraudenbach transitioned from Chairman of the Board to Lead Independent Director. Management characterised the changes as formalisation of existing day-to-day operating structure rather than a substantive shift, but the consolidation of COO and CFO under Ezzell concentrates financial and operational accountability into a single executive during a period of balance-sheet stress and divestiture execution.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged — the FY25 Form 10-K was filed December 15, 2025 within the statutory deadline and Q1 FY26 results were released January 29, 2026 on the originally scheduled date, with no Form 12b-25 extension reported. Reporting controls remain intact despite underlying operating and balance-sheet stress.

> Recent Issues & Restructuring-Relevant Developments: Subsequent to the Q1 FY26 release, results and outlook have continued to deteriorate. Q2 FY26 (10-Q for quarter ended March 31, 2026) revenue declined (8.5%) YoY to $442.3m, materially missing consensus of $489.2m by ~10%; income from operations fell (53.1%) to $7.6m from $16.3m, and net loss widened materially to ($12.9m) in Q2 FY26 from ($0.4m) in Q2 FY25 — a ~32x increase. H1 FY26 cumulative results showed $14.0m of restructuring and impairment charges (including a $5.8m trade name write-down related to a brand exit), operating cash flow use of ($23.8m), and a cash balance of $8.2m at March 31, 2026 — down (87.9%) YoY and structurally inadequate. Management revised FY26 guidance downward twice within a single quarter: (i) February 2026 post-Ocean Bio-Chem divestiture (revenue $1.78bn–$1.88bn, EPS $0.20–$0.70, from $1.83bn–$1.93bn and $0.25–$0.75 originally), and (ii) March 2026 narrowing to $0.45 EPS, $70m Adjusted EBITDA, $1.83bn revenue. Strategic and governance signals: CEO Anthony Aisquith publicly cited SSI industry data showing "double-digit declines" in OneWater's core competitive categories; Executive Chairman Austin Singleton transferred 15,988 shares to the Austin Singleton Irrevocable Trust on December 16, 2025 (estate planning, but signals reducing direct personal exposure during stress window); and industry M&A speculation has resurfaced around peer MarineMax (HZO), with OneWater itself having bid $2.5bn for MarineMax in mid-2024 — confirming the industry consolidation thesis remains live and either side could become a distressed M&A counterparty. No material litigation, regulatory enforcement, or labor disputes have been publicly disclosed; standard 10-K legal proceedings language only.

